WEBVTT

00:04.830 --> 00:08.630
DIANE:
This is about a plane crash.

00:08.670 --> 00:11.104
A Hammett GR—6 carrying

00:11.140 --> 00:15.429
35 passengers and five crew.

00:15.480 --> 00:19.109
All 40 dead.

00:19.150 --> 00:21.675
Many of their widows
and widowers are here today.

00:21.720 --> 00:24.245
And all want to know one thing.

00:24.290 --> 00:28.579
Why did this plane just drop
from the slq?

00:28.620 --> 00:30.281
Like Kyle Lidtke.

00:30.330 --> 00:34.551
He lost his wife
and two daughters in this crash.

00:34.600 --> 00:37.068
Now, the CEO
of Hammett Aerospace

00:37.100 --> 00:40.536
would have him believe
it's the pilot's fault,

00:40.570 --> 00:41.798
and not their plane.

00:41.840 --> 00:43.831
But we ask you to reject

00:43.870 --> 00:47.431
this cynical,
blame-the-victim defense,

00:47.480 --> 00:51.541
because this is
a very Simple case of...

00:51.580 --> 00:53.571
...a flawed airplane design.

00:55.550 --> 00:57.609
My co-counsel, Ms. Lockhart,

00:57.650 --> 01:00.312
represents the families
of the passengers.

01:00.360 --> 01:02.783
I represent the families
of the crew.

01:02.830 --> 01:05.185
But we decided
to combine our lawsuits

01:05.230 --> 01:08.358
because we agree on one thing.

01:08.400 --> 01:11.563
Hammett Aerospace

01:11.600 --> 01:15.138
put a jet into service
that they knew was defective.

01:15.170 --> 01:17.832
How do we know this?

01:17.870 --> 01:21.203
How do we know that they knew
their jet was defective?

01:22.750 --> 01:24.877
Because there is
a very brave whistleblower

01:24.910 --> 01:27.470
from within Hammett

01:27.520 --> 01:30.887
who's agreed to testify for us.

01:30.920 --> 01:32.478
(gunshot)

01:32.520 --> 01:35.455
Damn.

01:38.160 --> 01:41.152
Not to sound too cynical,
but this could be a good thing.

01:43.670 --> 01:45.729
Guilt-ridden
whistle-blower

01:45.770 --> 01:48.591
testifying from
beyond the grave?

01:48.640 --> 01:51.905
They didn't do a great job
cross-examining in the depo.

01:51.940 --> 01:56.604
And it's_ hard
to cross-examine a corpse.

01:56.650 --> 01:57.469
The problem was in the wings.

01:57.510 --> 01:59.819
_ _DIA_NE: _
The de-Icmg In the wrngs?
Yes.

01:59.850 --> 02:02.489
It was a system of tubes
that distributed fluid

02:02.520 --> 02:04.511
to de-ice the wings
during flight.

02:05.620 --> 02:06.814
Not bad.

02:06.860 --> 02:08.816
We admit this
Into evrdence.

02:08.860 --> 02:11.328
And avoid further
cross-examination.
Yup.

02:11.360 --> 02:13.351
Falling forward.

02:14.400 --> 02:16.721
Well, that's the problem.

02:16.770 --> 02:18.897
She's a great tutor.

02:18.930 --> 02:20.795
Grace's physics grades

02:20.840 --> 02:21.795
are the best this year.

02:21.840 --> 02:22.738
And where did you find her?

02:22.770 --> 02:24.806
The tutor Eli suggested her.

02:24.840 --> 02:26.899
And Grace is friends
with her now?

02:28.680 --> 02:29.772
Who, Grace or the tutor?

02:29.810 --> 02:31.300
The tutor.

02:31.350 --> 02:34.171
Well, I can find some tutor
referrals around here.

02:34.220 --> 02:35.278
No, that's okay.

02:35.320 --> 02:37.618
Let me handle it with
a flyswatter, not a bazooka.

02:37.650 --> 02:40.881
I didn't think I was handling it

02:40.920 --> 02:41.852
with a bazooka.

02:41.890 --> 02:43.881
(knocking)

02:43.930 --> 02:45.579
Uh, okay, we'll talk.

02:45.630 --> 02:46.824
I got to go.

02:46.860 --> 02:48.498
Yes, sir.

02:48.530 --> 02:50.623
David Lee's here.

02:50.670 --> 02:52.433
We need more
conference room space.

02:52.470 --> 02:54.631
I'm like an itinerant
farmer out here.

02:54.670 --> 02:56.729
WILL:
So, Alicia,

02:56.770 --> 02:58.761
David and I head up
the hiring committee,

02:58.810 --> 03:01.370
and we've decided the firm needs
a new first-year assoaate.

03:01.410 --> 03:02.775
So we want you
to interview and hire someone.

03:02.810 --> 03:05.643
Really?

03:05.680 --> 03:07.238
These are the new graduates

03:07.280 --> 03:09.817
from U of C.
See who you like.

03:09.850 --> 03:12.819
You want me _
to do the actual hIrIng?

03:12.860 --> 03:14.555
In consultation
with the committee.

03:14.590 --> 03:16.956
And you'll be mentoring him,
too, so choose well.

03:16.990 --> 03:18.821
Or her.

03:18.860 --> 03:20.851
Oh, Alicia, uh, I need

03:20.900 --> 03:23.892
to talk to you a minute
about the Cole divorce, hmm?

03:25.600 --> 03:27.761
Thank you for this.

03:27.800 --> 03:29.631
No, not me. David.

03:29.670 --> 03:31.900
I'm still supposed
to be tense with you, remember?

03:31.940 --> 03:35.398
And by the way,
I know how Celeste works.

03:35.440 --> 03:38.341
Don't worry about it.
No, she thrives on chaos.

03:38.380 --> 03:41.417
She'll say a lot of things about
me just to see how you react.

03:41.450 --> 03:43.941
Then I won't react.

03:47.020 --> 03:49.580
DAVID:
So,

03:49.630 --> 03:51.882
we can't use "Cole divorce"
as our cover word anymore

03:51.930 --> 03:53.488
because I actually
have a Cole divorce.

03:53.530 --> 03:54.952
Oh. Well, we don't need
a cover word.

03:55.000 --> 03:56.319
I'm still undecided about it.

03:56.370 --> 03:58.827
Ah, yes, the fiction
of separation.

03:58.870 --> 04:00.690
You're putting your kids

04:00.740 --> 04:02.537
in private school?

04:02.570 --> 04:04.902
New item in your
financial journal.

04:04.940 --> 04:06.771
I'm thinking of it, yes.

04:06.810 --> 04:08.505
That's $35,000 to 50 a year.

04:08.540 --> 04:10.599
I know.
My advice is, you don't.

04:10.650 --> 04:12.311
Thank you, but I'm fine.

04:12.350 --> 04:13.476
No, you don't
understand.

04:13.520 --> 04:14.669
I'm not your
accountant.

04:14.720 --> 04:16.779
You can overspend on
anything you like, but

04:16.820 --> 04:18.515
you need to get your husband
to pay half.

04:18.550 --> 04:19.949
I... Why?

04:19.990 --> 04:21.981
To preserve
your dependency.

04:22.020 --> 04:23.829
You pay that amount on your own,

04:23.860 --> 04:25.953
you lose your best argument
against spousal maintenance.

04:25.990 --> 04:28.299
Well, I'm not asking Peter
for spousal maintenance.

04:28.330 --> 04:29.558
No, not you. Him.

04:29.600 --> 04:31.989
(laughs)

04:32.030 --> 04:34.362
Hey, don't blame me.
You guys wanted equal treatment.

04:34.400 --> 04:35.594
Thank Gloria Steinem.

04:35.640 --> 04:36.937
Peter makes less

04:36.970 --> 04:38.608
in the State's Attorney office
than you.

04:38.640 --> 04:39.834
He could come after you
for support.

04:39.880 --> 04:42.804
Peter's not coming after me
for support.

04:42.850 --> 04:45.648
Alicia, he'll come after you
for everything.

04:45.680 --> 04:47.739
No, he wants the governorship.

04:47.780 --> 04:50.578
That's what Eli's plotting
over there right now.

04:50.620 --> 04:51.939
Give him the keynote.

04:51.990 --> 04:53.810
(laughs)

04:53.860 --> 04:55.612
Are you kidding?

04:55.660 --> 04:56.957
At the Democratic Convention?

04:56.990 --> 04:58.878
Peter has the
best story.

04:58.930 --> 05:00.898
He went to prison
on a trumped-up charge,

05:00.930 --> 05:02.864
fought it, and made it back
into office.

05:02.900 --> 05:04.492
It's a story of rebirth.

05:04.530 --> 05:05.497
Eli, he's a state's attorney.

05:05.530 --> 05:06.690
And Obama was

05:06.740 --> 05:08.696
a state senator
when he got the keynote.

05:08.740 --> 05:10.560
And a black man.

05:10.610 --> 05:13.329
Who is it?

05:13.380 --> 05:14.699
Who's what?

05:14.740 --> 05:15.934
Who are you championing?

05:15.980 --> 05:18.346
You must have somebody already.

05:18.380 --> 05:20.018
(sighs)

05:20.050 --> 05:21.517
Adam Spellman.

05:21.550 --> 05:24.018
Oh, come on!

05:24.050 --> 05:26.518
No to the State's Attorney,
but yes to a dogcatcher?

05:26.560 --> 05:27.709
He's not a dogcatcher.

05:27.760 --> 05:28.988
He's a strong businessman
with...

05:29.020 --> 05:30.351
You think that's

05:30.390 --> 05:32.028
what America wants
to see up on that dais?

05:32.060 --> 05:33.755
Eli, it's already in the works.
We're pushing Spellman.

05:33.800 --> 05:35.893
Don't worry about it.

05:35.930 --> 05:38.069
Peter Florrick's marriage
is his secret weapon,

05:38.100 --> 05:40.034
not some keynote address.

05:40.070 --> 05:42.766
So, how is she doing?

05:45.940 --> 05:49.068
They knew the de-icing fluid
tended to freeze

05:49.110 --> 05:50.702
in the wing lines,

05:50.750 --> 05:52.775
but they decided to save money

05:52.820 --> 05:54.742
and do nothing about it.

05:54.780 --> 05:56.680
We move to introduce
this deposition

05:56.720 --> 05:58.017
into evidence, Your Honor.

05:58.050 --> 05:59.915
And we object, Your
Honor. It's hearsay.

05:59.960 --> 06:02.622
We can't cross-examine
a corpse.
Really, Mr. Roda?

06:02.660 --> 06:04.059
I'm sorry, Your Honor.
Inelegantly put.

06:04.090 --> 06:06.991
But I can't
cross-examine
the deceased.

06:07.030 --> 06:07.928
DIANE:
Your Honor, Rule 212

06:07.960 --> 06:09.689
expressly permits the use

06:09.730 --> 06:11.618
of a recorded deposition
when a witness dies.

06:11.670 --> 06:13.831
But only if the court, in
its discretion, determines

06:13.870 --> 06:15.167
it wo_n't_do a _
substantial Injustice,

06:15.200 --> 06:17.100
such as in the case of perjury.

06:17.140 --> 06:19.802
Which is why, in the current
matter, I would direct

06:19.840 --> 06:22.400
the court's attention to
Mr. Ritter's suicide note.

06:22.450 --> 06:24.600
It consists of two lines.

06:24.650 --> 06:26.709
"It's a lie.
I'm sorry."

06:26.750 --> 06:28.809
Your Honor, Mr. Ritter's wife
was claiming

06:28.850 --> 06:30.738
he slept with
their 16-year-old baby-sitter.

06:30.790 --> 06:32.143
The note refers to that.

06:32.190 --> 06:33.259
We don't know that.

06:33.290 --> 06:35.952
He could be referring
to his testimony in this trial.

06:35.990 --> 06:37.821
At the very least,
the meaning is unclear.

06:37.860 --> 06:39.179
Unclear?
Oh, really?
Are you serious?

06:39.230 --> 06:40.754
I'm not prepared to
interpret the law...

06:40.800 --> 06:43.018
(overlapping chatter)

06:43.070 --> 06:44.594
You can all
wear yourselves down.

06:44.630 --> 06:45.790
Tell me when you're ready.

06:46.840 --> 06:48.159
What do we do now?

06:48.200 --> 06:49.565
We have other options.

06:49.610 --> 06:50.736
Like what?

06:50.770 --> 06:51.998
We'll _ask
for a continuance.

06:52.040 --> 06:53.837
We still have
our expert Witnesses.

06:53.880 --> 06:55.199
You thought they weren't enough.

06:55.240 --> 06:57.879
Hold them
accountable,

06:57.910 --> 07:01.641
please... for my wife
and daughters.

07:03.150 --> 07:05.641
Kalinda, what are you doing?

07:05.690 --> 07:07.681
Um, Eli business.
What do you need?

07:09.020 --> 07:11.022
Yeah, I'm already on it.

07:12.030 --> 07:14.225
Yeah?

07:14.260 --> 07:16.524
Adam Spellman--
do you know who that is?

07:16.570 --> 07:18.891
Adam Spellman.
A businessman.

07:18.930 --> 07:20.830
Head of the Chicago
Black Leadership Council.

07:20.870 --> 07:22.838
Yeah, I need you
to look into him.

07:22.870 --> 07:24.132
Look?
As in, find dirt.

07:24.170 --> 07:26.035
Why?

07:26.070 --> 07:28.106
He's the likely
keynote speaker at the next

07:28.140 --> 07:30.176
Democratic Convention, and if
he has a skeleton in his closet,

07:30.210 --> 07:31.700
I do not want him blowing up

07:31.750 --> 07:33.115
in the face
of the Democratic Committee.

07:33.150 --> 07:35.038
Really? How selfless of you.

07:35.080 --> 07:37.048
Yeah, well,
I'm a caring individual.

07:37.090 --> 07:38.785
Mm.

07:38.820 --> 07:40.185
I need it quick.

07:40.220 --> 07:42.051
Yeah. Everybody needs it quick.

07:43.160 --> 07:45.128
Ah.

07:45.160 --> 07:46.991
That was quick.

07:47.030 --> 07:49.055
It was a blind CC.

07:49.100 --> 07:52.024
Ritter e-mailed the CEO
about the de-icing problems,

07:52.070 --> 07:53.867
and on Ritter's copy,

07:53.900 --> 07:57.165
there were only two e-mail
addresses included in the CC.

07:57.210 --> 08:00.998
But on the CEO's copy,
he BCC'd someone else.

08:01.040 --> 08:03.577
CS at HeralquuityGroup?
Who's that?

08:05.980 --> 08:06.947
Oh, no.

08:06.980 --> 08:07.514
What?

08:07.550 --> 08:08.869
He's a client of ours

08:08.920 --> 08:09.887
from two years ago.

08:09.920 --> 08:12.138
He was the venture capitalist
on their IPO.

08:12.190 --> 08:13.612
CEO kept him in the loop.

08:13.660 --> 08:15.878
(sighs)
Great.

08:15.920 --> 08:17.785
What?

08:17.830 --> 08:19.286
Well, he's not the most
dependable of witnesses.

08:19.330 --> 08:21.025
He might not even talk to us.

08:21.060 --> 08:22.527
He won't.

08:22.570 --> 08:24.788
Call Alicia.

08:24.830 --> 08:25.694
Why?

08:25.730 --> 08:27.231
He'll talk to her.

08:27.270 --> 08:29.261
(indistinct chatter
and voice over PA system)

08:39.010 --> 08:40.773
(buzzer sounding)

08:40.820 --> 08:44.119
Here I didn't think we'd get
a chance to work together.

08:44.150 --> 08:47.119
See? Isn't this fun?

08:47.160 --> 08:50.027
So, you and I should
get some drinks,

08:50.060 --> 08:52.153
trade whore stories.

08:52.190 --> 08:53.726
Horror?

08:53.760 --> 08:55.751
Yeah. What did I say?

08:57.130 --> 08:59.792
He's not allowed to touch you,
or hand you anything.

08:59.840 --> 09:02.604
There's a panic button at the
table if there's any problems.

09:02.640 --> 09:04.767
That's not his style.
How much does he know?

09:04.810 --> 09:07.176
Nothing. I thought
I'd let you broach it.

09:07.210 --> 09:09.201
Just like Clarice
Starling, huh?

09:19.620 --> 09:23.021
Mrs. Florrick, what a pleasure.

09:37.870 --> 09:39.599
You seem well.

09:39.640 --> 09:41.835
Oh, under the circumstances,

09:41.880 --> 09:43.939
I, uh, do the best I can.

09:43.980 --> 09:45.743
(humming)

09:45.780 --> 09:47.668
You have a tattoo, I see.

09:47.720 --> 09:48.914
What?

09:48.950 --> 09:51.248
Oh. Oh, yeah.

09:51.290 --> 09:52.757
Oh, this...
oh, this old thing?

09:52.790 --> 09:54.610
I wanted William Blake's

09:54.660 --> 09:56.059
The Ancient of Days,

09:56.090 --> 09:58.650
but beggars really
can't be choosers here.

09:58.690 --> 10:02.251
And you, Mrs. Florrick--
I imagine you're well?

10:02.300 --> 10:05.326
Your husband's
back in office,

10:05.370 --> 10:07.133
you're thriving in
your profession.

10:07.170 --> 10:09.638
The world must be your oyster.

10:09.670 --> 10:12.161
I would say the grass
is always greener, but...

10:12.210 --> 10:13.871
(laughing):
Yes.

10:13.910 --> 10:17.869
Although, there's a refreshing
honesty to prison.

10:17.910 --> 10:20.219
People don't dissemble here,
they just take.

10:23.390 --> 10:25.210
My firm needs your help,
Mr. Sweeney.

10:25.250 --> 10:29.789
So, that's it for small talk?

10:29.830 --> 10:32.082
We're suing a company--
Hammett Aerospace.

10:32.130 --> 10:33.290
There was a plane crash.

10:33.330 --> 10:35.252
The Dorset crash, yes, I know.

10:35.300 --> 10:37.666
You were the financier
on their IPO.

10:37.700 --> 10:40.692
We had a witness who
knew there was a problem

10:40.740 --> 10:42.799
with the de-icing system
on the plane

10:42.840 --> 10:44.000
but he committed suicide.

10:44.040 --> 10:45.268
Oh, dear.

10:45.310 --> 10:47.198
Yes.

10:47.240 --> 10:51.301
Anyway, he was testifying
to a meeting you attended.

10:51.350 --> 10:55.013
And you were wondering if
I might testify in his stead?

10:55.050 --> 10:56.984
Yes.
Why me?

10:57.020 --> 10:58.749
Why not O.J.?

10:58.790 --> 11:00.678
Won't the jury be
likely to mistrust

11:00.720 --> 11:02.881
the word of a renowned
wife-killer?

11:02.930 --> 11:04.352
You were never convicted.

11:04.390 --> 11:05.288
(chuckles):
Oh, yes.

11:05.330 --> 11:09.096
One of those fine
distinctions in the law.

11:09.130 --> 11:12.930
Imprisoned on something
I didn't even do.

11:12.970 --> 11:14.892
I hate irony.

11:14.940 --> 11:17.329
I heard America's
irony-free these days.

11:17.370 --> 11:19.361
Yes, it's been outlawed.

11:19.410 --> 11:21.435
(chuckles)

11:25.480 --> 11:28.176
I like you, Alicia.

11:28.220 --> 11:30.245
Why don't you like me?

11:31.290 --> 11:33.349
You killed your wife.

11:33.390 --> 11:36.450
And there's nothing
I can do about that?

11:40.230 --> 11:41.390
Testify.

11:41.430 --> 11:44.422
Would that help you?

11:44.470 --> 11:47.030
It would help 40 families
suing Hammett Aerospace.

11:47.070 --> 11:49.959
Yes, and I'm sure
they're all adorable, but...

11:50.010 --> 11:51.363
will it help you?

11:54.810 --> 11:56.038
Yes.

11:56.080 --> 11:59.072
Then, of course, I'll help.

11:59.110 --> 12:01.476
(loud rock music playing)

12:04.350 --> 12:06.489
(rock music continues)

12:08.490 --> 12:11.288
Oh, thank you
for waiting.

12:11.330 --> 12:13.457
(panting):
Work.

12:15.260 --> 12:18.320
Um... I think you're doing
a great job as a tutor.

12:18.370 --> 12:19.894
Ijust...

12:19.940 --> 12:22.363
Do you, um, want something?
You want a latte or...

12:22.400 --> 12:23.799
Oh, no.

12:23.840 --> 12:27.105
So, these... videos,

12:27.140 --> 12:28.505
um, that you make,

12:28.540 --> 12:30.804
these dance videos, um,

12:30.850 --> 12:32.977
they're just...

12:36.580 --> 12:38.389
How old are you, Jennifer?

12:38.420 --> 12:40.809
I'm 22.
And...

12:40.860 --> 12:42.179
you and Grace
have become friends?

12:42.220 --> 12:44.154
Yes.
And these, um,

12:44.190 --> 12:47.057
dance... videos, uh,

12:47.100 --> 12:48.499
are f...

12:48.530 --> 12:50.395
um, what are they for?

12:51.830 --> 12:53.388
The Internet.

12:54.440 --> 12:55.395
Uh-huh.

12:55.440 --> 12:57.203
You make money off of them?

12:57.240 --> 12:59.003
No.

12:59.040 --> 13:00.871
You just do them?

13:00.910 --> 13:02.172
Yes.

13:02.210 --> 13:04.303
I don't understand.

13:05.580 --> 13:08.970
I like doing them.

13:11.390 --> 13:15.087
Okay. Um, Jennifer, I...

13:15.120 --> 13:18.283
I just want you to be a tutor.

13:18.330 --> 13:21.424
Okay? I-I want you
to work with Grace
on her homework.

13:21.460 --> 13:24.327
I don't want Grace making
these videos with you anymore.

13:26.430 --> 13:28.034
Okay.

13:28.070 --> 13:31.005
Is that it?

13:31.040 --> 13:32.302
Yes.

13:43.590 --> 13:45.148
ELI:
Oh, my God,

13:45.190 --> 13:46.282
you're good!

13:46.320 --> 13:47.355
Thanks.

13:47.390 --> 13:49.358
So, Adam Spellman,

13:49.390 --> 13:51.881
a Democrat,
really gave money

13:51.930 --> 13:53.921
to support the Defense
of Marriage Act?

13:53.960 --> 13:55.450
His wife did-- she's
a devout Baptist,

13:55.500 --> 13:57.468
and knew it would
be a problem.

13:57.500 --> 13:59.593
That's why the money
came through her company.

13:59.630 --> 14:02.394
And then they tried
to hide it. (laughs)

14:02.440 --> 14:05.204
I mean, I think this
is good that the DNC

